		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Iron law of oligarchy</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>The <b>iron law of oligarchy</b> is a political theory, first developed by the German <a href="/wiki/Syndicalism" title="Syndicalism">syndicalist</a> <a href="/wiki/Sociology" title="Sociology">sociologist</a> <a href="/wiki/Robert_Michels" title="Robert Michels">Robert Michels</a> in his 1911 book, <i><a href="/wiki/Political_Parties_(book)" title="Political Parties (book)">Political Parties</a></i>. It states that all forms of <a href="/wiki/Organization" title="Organization">organization</a>, regardless of how <a href="/wiki/Democratic" title="Democratic" class="mw-redirect">democratic</a> or <a href="/wiki/Autocratic" title="Autocratic" class="mw-redirect">autocratic</a> they may be at the start, will eventually and inevitably develop into <a href="/wiki/Oligarchy" title="Oligarchy">oligarchies</a>. The reasons for this are the technical indispensability of leadership, the tendency of the leaders to organize themselves and to consolidate their interests; the gratitude of the led towards the leaders, and the general immobility and passivity of the masses.</p>
